{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c9e6a4c4-f444-43e5-a5b3-8f58af017c39","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`workload update`** downloads and installs the latest versions of your installed workloads, matching them to your current SDK. This is what you need after an SDK update leaves workloads behind.\n- **`workload repair`** only *reinstalls* workloads at their current versions to fix corrupted installations — it won't bring them up to date.\n\nAfter updating, you can verify with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload list\n```\n\nIf the build still fails, check that the `maui` workload is present in the list and consider running `dotnet workload install maui` explicitly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fb7155ba-c078-42e3-99ac-99ed4eaca2f1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for advice about .NET MAUI workload issues after an SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.\n\nKey differences:\n- `dotnet workload update` — updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions for the current SDK band.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted or broken installations, but does NOT update them.\n\nSince the user's issue is that workloads are **out of date** after an SDK update, `dotnet workload update` is the right choice.","outputTokens":299},"id":"3c370760-974e-40bb-a6c9-a17a937f0fd8","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:46:09.905Z","parentId":"46def5d1-f6c8-4814-a552-db66b3ec2c25"}
